What Is Buyer Intent Data and Why It Matters Now
Let's start with the basics. Buyer intent data refers to signals and indicators that show when a prospect is actively researching, evaluating, or preparing to make a purchase decision. These signals come from multiple sources website behavior, content downloads, search queries, social media activity, industry news mentions, and more.

But here's what makes 2026 different: the technology that collects and analyzes this data has become exponentially more sophisticated. We're not just looking at whether someone visited your website anymore. We're examining complex behavioral patterns, purchase signals, and competitive considerations that paint a complete picture of where a prospect stands in their buying journey.

Understanding the Foundation of Intent Data

Think of intent data as the difference between knowing someone walked into a store versus knowing they walked directly to the electronics section, picked up three different laptops, read the specifications on each one, compared prices, and called a friend to discuss. That level of granularity is what modern intent data provides.

There are typically two types of intent data that matter to B2B companies:

First-party intent data comes from your own channels your website, email interactions, customer data platform, and CRM system. This tells you what prospects are doing when they're directly engaging with you.

Third-party intent data comes from external sources industry publications, research platforms, social networks, and specialized intent providers. This reveals what prospects are doing across the broader digital landscape, including competitive research and general industry exploration.

Together, these create a comprehensive picture of buyer readiness and interest.

